Fix minor code issue pointed out during talk at LCA

This commit fixes an issue pointed out during the questions when I gave
the talk at LCA. [1] They correctly pointed out that I was passing the
classical register to the oracle circuit definition even when it wasn't
used. During the talk I missed what he was mentioning and didn't
understand the question. This commit fixes that to avoid confusion so
the oracle circuit definition only relies on the registers it uses.
While passing an extra register to the definition doesn't do anything if
it's not used in the circuit, this was a source of confusion so this
addresses that.

[1] https://youtu.be/th4TDYX6xoc?t=2402

Update Part.1.E.6.containers.ipynb

优化表述。原表述容易产生理解错误。

通过测试发现，max()与min()函数只能在“具有相同类型值的列表”（都是数字或者都是字符串）中进行比较。

在具有混合类型值的列表上，使用max()与min()函数会报错：TypeError: '>' not supported between instances of 'str' and 'int'。例如，例子中的c_list列表使用max()与min函数就会报错。

实际情况是，max()与min()函数并不能“比较字符和数字”。它们只能在字符之间或者数字之间进行比较。因此，修改表述后，更容易理解上不出现偏差。

Now downloading checkpoint, also more markdown.

- Added some utilities inspired by the fastai notebooks.
- Ended up using wget instead of the HTTP library 'Just', as it wasn't
handling redirects nicely. It would write the contents of the redirect
landing page into the file to which it was redirecting. I thought I did
something wrong when I made the tar, but finally found that there was
html at the beginning of the file. wget works perfectly fine in this
scenario!
- Added a bit more prose to the last part of the notebook. Also improved
the subplot code to maximize screen real estate.

Lots of organizing and documentation

- Cleaned up code a bit.
- Added more markdown.
- Added a gitignore.
- Will set up downloading of checkpoint file next.

Clean up and markdown.

- Refactored a bit of code
- Started adding markdown cells.

Finally solved clipping issue.

- The aberrant pixel issue was solved by cliping the image after every
gradient update to be no greater or less than [-mean, mean] where mean
is the imagenet per color channel mean. The gradients would push values
past that range and would overexcite the network causing those regions
to clip to 255 in one or more channel.
- Using 512 images now.
- Added some test images.
- Cleaned up some code.
- Started adding some prose but will work on that in the next commit.

Got back to a good point.

- Now able to achieve pretty good results with old hyperparameters.
- Dialed down learning rate a bit.
- Still seeing some aberrant pixels, but fewer than before.
- Not sure how easy it would be to change style to content ratio.
Honestly need to look into implementing L-BFGS, but there would probably
be memory issues.
- I tried hooking up total variation, but it explodes memory for some
reason. I think there's a memory leak in autodiff somewhere. All it does
is makes a few basic tensor operations. Might ask on forums, but I'm
pretty much doing the identical thing in pyTorch and TF python with
about a 3rd of the memory footprint.
- Anyhow this might be as good as it gets for now.
- Will try some different images with different color content to see how
they look.

Commiting things in a broken state.

- Tried a new approach but can't quite seem to get things close to where
I was before.
- Got things previously working pretty decently sans a few
over-saturated pixels here or there.
- Stupidly forgot to commit said approach but know how things were set
up.
- Will try to get that same approach working on VGG19 which is what I've
moved to now. Same activation layers are being used for style and
content.
- The approach I'm trying in this commit was an attempt to approximate
this:
https://www.tensorflow.org/alpha/tutorials/generative/style_transfer
There are some things I'm uncertain about with this approach that
warrants further investigation at some point.
- It seems like the target features for style and content are computed
with BGR and Caffe style input values, i.e.
RGB->BGR -> img[0,1]->[0,255]-imgnet_mean. However the image being
optimized seems to be a [0,1] rgb image that gets converted to the
aforementioned format on input, but seems to be getting optimized in its
original form. This doesn't make sense to me since the gradients will be
mixed up wrt the color channels. I know that my previous solution was
pretty close to perfect considering I was using Adam. The results looked
better than those in the aforementioned tutorial post. There was very
little artefacting aside from the odd single pixel aberrations. These
pixels seemed to pop up around where the more saturated regions of the
content and style image were. The effect was pretty minimal, but I'm
not sure how things would fare if I bumped up from 224 to 512 or
something.
